<div class="penelope">
  <img src="/img/welcomingcat.png" alt="Penelope the Neocities cat, waving hello">
  <div class="penelope-Bubble">
    <p>Hi! I'm Penelope, the Neocities cat. I'm going to teach you how to make your very own website. No experience needed &mdash; let's jump right in!</p>
  </div>
</div>

<p>Here's a secret: <strong>every web page is just a text file.</strong> When you visit a website, your browser downloads a text file and follows the instructions inside it to draw the page on your screen.</p>

<p>The box on the right contains a real web page &mdash; a small one, but the same kind of text file that every site on the internet is made of. Below it, you can see how a browser displays it, live.</p>

<p>You don't need to understand everything in the box yet. Just notice the words <strong>Hello World!</strong> in the middle &mdash; that's the part visitors see.</p>

<div class="your-Turn">
  <h4><i class="fa fa-pencil" aria-hidden="true"></i> Your turn</h4>
  <ol>
    <li>In the code box, find the words <code>Hello World!</code></li>
    <li>Replace them with a greeting of your own &mdash; maybe <em>Welcome to my website!</em> or anything you like.</li>
    <li>Watch the preview underneath update as you type. That's your page changing!</li>
    <li>When you're happy, click <strong>Check My Work</strong>.</li>
  </ol>
</div>

<div class="bonus-Box">
  <h4>What's with the pointy brackets?</h4>
  <p>The words wrapped in angle brackets, like <code><%= '<body>' %></code>, are called <strong>tags</strong>. They're the instructions that tell the browser what everything is. We'll meet them properly on the next page.</p>
</div>

<script>
  function lessonCheck(doc, html) {
    var text = bodyText(doc)

    if(/hello world/i.test(text))
      return {ok: false, message: 'I still see &ldquo;Hello World!&rdquo; in there. Replace it with your own words, then check again.'}

    if(text == '')
      return {ok: false, message: 'The page is looking a little empty! Type a greeting between ' + codeSample('<body>') + ' and ' + codeSample('</body>') + ' &mdash; or click Reset This Step to start over.'}

    return {ok: true, message: 'You just edited a real web page!'}
  }
</script>
